<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-708-628  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 708 628.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Sept 25 1989 v23 n39 p107(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Document imaging: the right fit? (includes related articles onproductivity and video imaging)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Keating, Wick.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Document imaging, the replacement of paper documents and fileswith digitized images of the originals, is more suitable for someapplications than others.andP;  The technology is more appropriate toapplications for which paper cannot be eliminated through other,less expensive forms of automation such as electronic mail andelectronic data interchange.andP;  Imaging is a good choice when thereare large amounts of paper produced, when data cannot be keyed,such as signatures or drawings.andP;  Imaging is also appropriate fordata that needs to be frequently accessed and retrieved, or whenextensive processing is required.andP;  Imaging is used wheninformation is critical, when errors would be too costly.andP;  Forexample, mortgage application processing is an ideal use, wherethere are numerous documents that need to be scrutinized quickly.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Imaging TechnologyProductivityMISErrorsCost Benefit Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   Indications that image processing is needed. (table)A typical document imaging system. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>